    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A type of glass characterized by its mainly greenish, turquoise, yellow, brown-green, or smoky black color accented by air bubbles, streaks of pink and white, and speckles of aventurine. To produce Clutha glassware, a worker used a gather of pale ruby or pale yellow glass, then rolled it over a marver lightly sprinkled with bits of colored glass and mica flakes. The gather was reheated and blown and tooled into the finished product. It was originally made by James Couper &amp; Sons, Glasgow. It is called "Clutha" from Gaelic for "cloudy."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
